    <p>Electrical hazards are responsible for thousands of accidents and fires annually. By understanding and implementing proper electrical safety measures, you can significantly reduce the risk to your home and family.</p>

    <h2>Common Electrical Hazards in the Home</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Overloaded circuits and outlets</li>
        <li>Damaged or frayed cords</li>
        <li>Water near electrical devices</li>
        <li>Faulty wiring and outdated systems</li>
        <li>Improper use of extension cords</li>
        <li>Childproofing issues</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Essential Safety Practices</h2>

    <h3>1. Protect Your Outlets</h3>
    <p>Use outlet covers and GFCI (Ground Fault Circuit Interrupter) outlets in areas near water, such as kitchens, bathrooms, and outdoor areas. These outlets automatically shut off if they sense a ground fault.</p>

    <h3>2. Inspect Cords Regularly</h3>
    <p>Check all electrical cords in your home for signs of damage, including cracks, fraying, or burns. Replace damaged cords immediately rather than attempting repairs.</p>

    <h3>3. Avoid Overloading Outlets</h3>
    <p>Never plug multiple high-power appliances into a single outlet. Use power strips with surge protection for additional devices, but don't daisy-chain them.</p>

    <h3>4. Keep Water Away From Electricity</h3>
    <p>Never use electrical devices or appliances near water. Keep electrical outlets and switches away from sinks and bathtubs. Use portable appliances in the bathroom with caution.</p>

    <h3>5. Use Surge Protectors</h3>
    <p>Electrical surges from lightning or power fluctuations can damage appliances and create fire hazards. Surge protectors help safeguard your devices.</p>

    <h3>6. Childproof Your Home</h3>
    <p>Use safety outlet covers and teach children about electrical dangers. Keep cords out of reach and secured to prevent tripping hazards.</p>

    <h2>Warning Signs You Need Professional Help</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Frequently tripping circuit breakers</li>
        <li>Outlets or switches that are warm to the touch</li>
        <li>Flickering lights or dimming appliances</li>
        <li>Burning smells or scorch marks</li>
        <li>Electrical shocks when touching switches or outlets</li>
        <li>Outdated wiring or two-prong outlets</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If you notice any of these signs, contact a licensed electrician immediately. <strong>Matria's experienced electricians in Pretoria and Johannesburg are available 24/7 for any electrical concerns.</strong></p>

    <h2>When to Call a Professional</h2>
    <p>Always hire a licensed electrician for:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Installing new outlets or circuits</li>
        <li>Upgrading your electrical panel</li>
        <li>Any major rewiring work</li>
        <li>Troubleshooting electrical problems</li>
        <li>SABS compliance inspections</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Electrical safety is not an area for DIY experimentation. Professional installation and maintenance ensure your family's safety and compliance with South African electrical standards.</p>
